sols_latex:
The solution of the differential equation $\frac{dy}{dt} = ky$ is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle y(t) = y(0) \cdot e^{kt}
\end{align*}

where in this case $y$ is the number of viral particles, $t$ is the time
in days, and $k$ is some constant.

We are given that $\displaystyle y(0) = 1000,\, k = 0.05$. Thus we have
$\displaystyle y(t) = 1000e^{0.05t}$.

Solving for $t$ when $\displaystyle y(t) = 350000$ yields:

\begin{align*}
350000 &= 1000e^{0.05t}
\\ 350 &= e^{0.05t}
\\ \ln350 &= 0.05t
\\ t &= {\color{blue} \frac{\ln350}{0.05} \,\,\mathrm{days}}
\end{align*}

